version: 1
display_name: PHTN-50-000224 - The Photon operating system must not respond to IPv4 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) echoes sent to a broadcast address.
global_description: |-
  Responding to broadcast (ICMP) echoes facilitates network mapping and provides a vector for amplification attacks.
osfinger:
  - VMware Photon OS-5
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - PHTN-50-000224
  srg:
    - SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227
  cci:
    - CCI-000366
  nist:
    - CM-6 b
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_photon_5:
    type: custom
    desc: The Photon operating system must not respond to IPv4 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) echoes sent to a broadcast address.
    control_id: PHTN-50-000224
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      At the command line, run the following command to verify ICMP echoes sent to a broadcast address are ignored:

      # /sbin/sysctl net.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts

      Example result:

      net.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts = 1

      If the "net.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts" kernel parameter is not set to "1", this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      Responding to broadcast (ICMP) echoes facilitates network mapping and provides a vector for amplification attacks.
    remediation: |-
      Navigate to and open:

      /etc/sysctl.d/zz-stig-hardening.conf

      Add or update the following line:

      net.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts = 1

      At the command line, run the following command to load the new configuration:

      # /sbin/sysctl --load /etc/sysctl.d/zz-stig-hardening.conf

      Note: If the file zz-stig-hardening.conf does not exist it must be created.
